File: e2e/browser-tools.e2e.ts, approximately line 2670.

The existing test at line ~2670 is:
```
test('extension_get_side_panel returns { open: false } when side panel is not open', async ({ mcpServer, ... }) => {
  ...
  const result = await callToolExpectSuccess(mcpClient, mcpServer, 'extension_get_side_panel');
  expect(result.open).toBe(false);
});
```

Add a companion test that:
1. Opens the side panel using the openSidePanel helper from helpers.ts
2. Calls extension_get_side_panel
3. Asserts result.open === true
4. Closes the side panel page

Note: The side panel detection works by checking if any extension pages with the side panel URL are open. In Playwright, opening the side panel URL via `context.newPage()` + `page.goto('chrome-extension://.../side-panel/side-panel.html')` should be detected. Import { openSidePanel } from './helpers.js' for this.

IMPORTANT: The extension_get_side_panel tool may detect the panel by checking extension views or ports. In Playwright's test environment, the side panel is opened as a regular page (not via chrome.sidePanel API), so the detection mechanism might not work the same way. If the tool always returns { open: false } in the test environment regardless, the test should document this limitation and skip with a comment. Read the tool's implementation first (search for 'extension_get_side_panel' or 'get_side_panel' in platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/ and platform/browser-extension/src/background.ts) to understand the detection mechanism before writing the test.
